谈到友谊和竞争，雄性海豚知道好团队球员是谁。 Bristol大学研究人员在自然通信中发表的新发现，揭示了男性海豚在团队合作投资的基础上形成了团队成员的社会理念。 Bristol研究人员，来自苏黎世大学和马萨诸塞大学的同事，在鲨鱼湾，西澳大利亚海豚人口中使用了30年的观测数据，以及声音播放实验，以评估如何回答其同盟的其他男性的呼叫网络。
  来自布里斯托尔＆＃39的高级讲师斯蒂芬妮国王博士说：曾经研究过研究的生物科学学院，说：＆＃34;社会动物可以具备与同一物种成员分类关系的复杂方式。在我们自己的社会中，我们使用社会知识将个人分类为有意义的群体，如体育队和政治盟友。瓶颈海豚在人类外部形成最复杂的联盟，我们想知道他们如何分类这些关系。＆＃34;
  Simon Allen博士，Bristol＆＃39;生物科学学院的研究员贡献，他们补充说：＆＃34;我们在海豚群体上方飞过无人机，在声音播放期间记录他们的行为，跟踪水下的运动揭示Dolphins如何回应其盟友网络中其他男性呼叫的新颖洞察。＆＃34;
  男性对所有持续帮助他们过去的所有盟友都反应了，即使他们不打击目前亲密的朋友，也是如此。另一方面，他们没有强烈反应谁曾经努力帮助他们在过去始终如一地帮助他们，即使他们是朋友。这表明的是这些海豚形成了社会概念＆＃39;团队成员资格＆＃39;根据共享合作历史分类盟友。
  国王博士说：＆＃34;这些概念通过经验发展，并且可能在早期人类的合作行为中发挥作用。我们的研究结果表明，基于合作的概念对人类并非独一无二，而且在其他动物社会中也发生在非亲属之间的广泛合作。＆＃34;

note_en:
When it comes to friendships and rivalries, male dolphins know who the good team players are. New findings, published in  Nature Communications by University of Bristol researchers, reveal that male dolphins form a social concept of team membership based on cooperative investment in the team.    The Bristol researchers, with colleagues from the University of Zurich and University of Massachusetts, used 30 years of observational data from a dolphin population in Shark Bay, Western Australia, and sound playback experiments to assess how   responded to the calls of other males from their alliance network.
  Dr. Stephanie King, Senior Lecturer from Bristol&#39;s School of Biological Sciences who led the research, said: &#34;Social animals can possess sophisticated ways of classifying relationships with members of the same species. In our own society, we use social knowledge to classify individuals into meaningful groups, like sports teams and political allies. Bottlenose dolphins form the most complex alliances outside humans, and we wanted to know how they classify these relationships.&#34;
  Dr. Simon Allen, Research Fellow at Bristol&#39;s School of Biological Sciences, who contributed to the study, added: &#34;We flew drones above dolphin groups, recording their behavior during the sound playbacks, tracking their movements underwater and revealing novel insights into how dolphins respond to the calls of other males in their network of allies.&#34;
  Males responded strongly to all of the allies that had consistently helped them out in the past, even if they weren&#39;t currently close friends. On the other hand, they didn&#39;t respond strongly to   who hadn&#39;t consistently helped them out in the past, even if they were friends. What this shows is that these dolphins form social concepts of &#39;team membership&#39;, categorizing allies according to a shared cooperative history.
  Dr. King said: &#34;Such concepts develop through experience and likely played a role in the cooperative behavior of early humans. Our results show that cooperation-based concepts are not unique to humans, but also occur in other animal societies with extensive cooperation between non-kin.&#34;
